		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Calabar&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Kingvince, the subject of AA points, when to get them and what to buy first, is about as touchy a gaming subject and religion and politics are in real life.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ask 20 people and you’ll not only get 20 different answers you’re also like to have at least 10 of them arguing about it.  In general, AA points were introduced to give players something else to spend their experience on instead of just reaching the level cap and having nothing to do.  You can spend these points on some very nice abilities.  As a shaman, its almost universally agreed among our class, yes you may gasp at this point, that your first goal should be Cannibalize Five.  I can tell you from personal experience that it’s a game altering ability.  You can still run out of manna using Canni 5, but you have to work a lot harder to do so.  Personally I stopped leveling in my early 50s to get Run 3.  AAs at that level take a relatively long time to gain, but I’ve never regretted it.  Run 3 will enable you to outrun most mobs even when indoors or when your SoW runs out in the middle of a strategic retreat.  Then I leveled to 61 for my new and improved puppy spell and set my XP bar to 100% AA XP until I got Canni 5.  Some people will tell you to level to 65 before doing any AA points.  This works well for some and not so well for others.  It just depends on your gaming style and the level of the players you usually group with.  <br><br>As for gaining skill; you can do this at any level.  For spell skills all you are talking about is time.  You don’t need to cast spells on mobs for your spell skills to improve.  Just find a nice comfortable spot to stand your character, stick a three-hour movie into the DVD, have a soda and some snacks within arms reach and start practicing those spells.  Take a look at your lowest level spells and find one for the class of spell you wish to work on that cost the least amount of manna.  Summon food is a good one as is Sense Animal.  Now cast this spell over and over and over and over until you are about ready to toss your computer out the window.  Your spell skill will eventually improve.  Just be mindful of the skill cap based upon your level.  It’s frustrating enough to practice a spell skill that can raise, no use killing yourself over a skill that’s reached its cap.  Oh, and should you choose a low level damage spell to practice with, you can either target yourself or you can target any NPC in the Plane of Knowledge.  For some reason the people who work there are extremely tolerant of people casting spells at them. Perhaps they are very well paid.  Whatever the reason they won’t attack you.  If you wish to test this out yourself, do what I did.  Stand next to a port stone and wait for a wondering NPC to pass within spell range.  <br><br>Combat skills are the ones that are a real pain to raise.  You have to attack dark blue or higher-level mobs in order to gain weapons and attack skill at a decent rate and you have to be attacked by said mobs to gain defense skills.  And as a shaman, especially one who slows for groups, your most important combat skill is your defense skill.  This skill adds to your armor class and help keep you alive.  Like any skill, the better your skill gets the slower it’ll rise.  Your character level has nothing, as such, to do with your learning your skills.  However, as you become higher and higher level the availability of mobs to fight that won’t kill you outright becomes more of a challenge.  The mobs introduced with PoP, for example, hit really really hard.  So practicing your skills there, while certainly possible, becomes much more risky.  This is why most people suggest keeping all your skills maxed each level if you can possibly do so.  Its great advice, but I’ve never managed to keep even one weapon skill maxed per level, much less all of them.  So it all kind of falls apart when put to the test, at least for me.  <br><br>However, if you don’t mind a mind numbing camp, I can tell you a good place to go for combat experience once you hit level 60.  This is where I went at level 61, with my brave new puppy, to gain AA points and to cap out my combat skills.  There are several clusters of mushrooms in Fungus Grove that you can single pull once you hit 60th level.  What I would do was park my puppy a good distance from one of them, equip whatever weapon I was trying to train and pull single mushrooms with my best slow spell.  The shrooms are casters and tend to stop on their way back to your camp to cast on you.  This should give you the time to cast a DoT on them.  They are usually really ticked at you for that and will ignore your pup in order to express their displeasure upon your person.  The shrooms will come and beat on your, which you should be sure to thank them for as this will raise your defense skill.  Unfortunately they will cast a slow spell on you, which will slow down your weapon skill gain.  But if you have enough magical defense this may not be a problem for you.  They will also turn you into a giant mushroom, but other than rooting you and working as a DoT it’s not a big deal.  Depending on your equipment, and your defense skill of course, the shrooms can do a fair amount of damage to you.  So keep the DoT or DoTs on them and make sure to give your puppy a pair of fangs, I use a couple of rusty weapons, so he’ll do maximum damage.  Once the shroom is dead heal yourself up and go pull another.  <br><br>As Fendergat pointed out, many shaman tend to group a lot before reaching 50th level.  For myself, I soloed to about 36 and I’ve almost always grouped every since, only soloing to work on my skills.  So many shaman find their combat skills becoming a source of embarrassment.  If you jump into combat a lot as you level you’ll have less catch-up work to do later on.  As with almost everything in this game, it all comes down to your play style.<br><br>If you should wish to find out even more about our class, you might wish to visit this site as well: <a href="http://forums.interealms.com/shaman/" target="akztarg">http://forums.interealms.com/shaman/</a><br><br>Best of luck,<br></p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br /><b>Logan</b> - Human Rogue (53) ~~~~~~~~ <b>Dombur</b> - Dwarf Priest (35)<br><b>Randar</b> - Human Paladin (41) ~~~~~~~ <b>Badger</b> - Gnome Mage (20)<br><b>Shadowfang</b> - NE Druid (23) ~~~~~~~ <b>Farli</b> - Dwarf Hunter (32)<br><br>Etcetera... Etcetra... Etcetra...</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
